rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:33
rsbNotes.text: 78:33 like a breath. This word is the same as found in the opening words of Ecclesiastes: “vanity” (Eccl. 1:2). It describes the world apart from God and under the curse of the Fall. Apart from God we have nothing: only the fear of death and the void.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:37
rsbNotes.text: 78:37 faithful to his covenant. See v. 10. God initiated a relationship with Israel through His grace, and then revealed His will to them through His law, including the curses and blessings of the covenant. The people disobeyed the law and brought on themselves God’s judgment.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:40
rsbNotes.text: 78:40 often they rebelled. Examples include Num. 11; 14; 16.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:44–51
rsbNotes.text: 78:44–51 He lists six of the plagues of Egypt.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:52
rsbNotes.text: 78:52 like a flock. See Ps. 77:20.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:54–64
rsbNotes.text: 78:54–64 God blessed them with the Promised Land, but they quickly forgot Him.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 78:55
rsbNotes.text: 78:55 He drove out nations. Israel fought, but the faithful knew that it was God, the Divine Warrior, who actually won the victories against the enemies. The story of the defeat of Jericho is a model for the battles of the conquest under Joshua (Josh. 5:13–6:27).
